(133, '31', 'Mizoram: \"The Land of the Highlanders\"', 'general', 'mizoram-the-land-of-the-highlanders', 'mizoram-1677520965644047.jpeg', 'MIZORAM', '\"Discover the picturesque beauty of Mizoram with GB International. From its stunning natural landscapes to its vibrant culture and heritage, Mizoram has something for everyone. Explore the state\'s charming villages, indulge in local cuisine, and witness its vibrant festivals. Let GB International take you on an unforgettable journey through Mizoram\'s hidden gems.\"', '<p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mizoram is a state located in northeastern India, known for its rich history and diverse culture. The state has been shaped by a variety of influences, including the British colonial era, the influence of neighboring countries, and the traditions of the state\'s many ethnic groups. Often overlooked by tourists, but it has a lot to offer for those who are willing to explore it. The state is known for its tranquil atmosphere, diverse culture, and beautiful landscapes.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">One of the most important periods in Mizoram\'s history is the British colonial era. The British established their control over the region in the late 19th century, and their influence can still be seen in the state\'s architecture and culture. Many of the state\'s public buildings, such as government offices and churches, were built during this period and are now considered historical landmarks.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mizoram is also known for its </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">diverse ethnic groups</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">, each with its own unique customs and traditions. The </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mizo people</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">, who make up the majority of the state\'s population, have a rich cultural heritage that includes traditional dances, music, and festivals. The state is also home to a significant number of other ethnic groups, including the </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Hmar, Lai, and Chakma people</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">One of the most unique things about Mizoram is its people. The Mizo people have a strong sense of community and are known for their warm hospitality. Visitors will find themselves welcomed with open arms and will have a chance to experience the local culture firsthand. The state is also home to several ethnic groups, each with its own unique customs and traditions, making it a melting pot of culture.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mizoram is also a great destination for adventure seekers. The state is home to several trekking trails, including the famous </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Blue Mountain</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">, which is the</span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> highest peak in Mizoram</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">. The state also has several rivers and lakes that offer opportunities for </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">rafting, kayaking, and fishing. </strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Phawngpui National Park</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> is also a great destination for wildlife enthusiasts, as it is home to a variety of flora and fauna, including several rare and endangered species.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">For those interested in history, Mizoram has several historical sites that are worth visiting. The </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mizoram State Museum</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> is a great place to learn about the state\'s rich cultural heritage and history. Visitors can also take a tour of the nearby Solomon\'s Temple, which is an important religious site for the Mizo people.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">One of the most important cultural traditions in Mizoram is the annual</span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> Chapchar Kut festival</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">, which is celebrated by the Mizo people to mark the end of the winter and the arrival of spring. The festival is celebrated with traditional dances, music, and feasts.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The state is also known for its vibrant music scene, which is influenced by a variety of traditional and contemporary styles. The state is home to many talented musicians and singers, who perform a wide range of music, from traditional folk songs to modern pop and rock. The state is also known for its t</span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">raditional crafts, such as bamboo weaving and blacksmithing.</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> These crafts are passed down from generation to generation and are an important part of the state\'s cultural heritage. A rich </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Christian heritage</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">, with Christianity being the dominant religion. The state has many churches and mission centers, that are not only religious places but also centers of cultural activities.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">In conclusion, it is a state with a rich and diverse history and culture. From the British colonial era to the many ethnic groups, from the Chapchar Kut festival to the traditional crafts, from the vibrant music scene to the Christian heritage, Mizoram has a lot to offer to those who are interested in exploring the history and culture of northeastern India.</span></p><p><strong>Cuisine</strong></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mizoram is known for its diverse and flavorful cuisine. The state\'s cuisine is influenced by the many ethnic groups that call Mizoram home, as well as the abundance of local ingredients and traditional cooking methods. One of the most popular dishes in Mizoram is bamboo shoot dishes, as the state is known for its abundance of bamboo. Bamboo shoots are used in many traditional dishes, such as </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">bamboo shoots and fish curry, bamboo shoots and pork curry, and bamboo shoots and dal (lentil) curry.</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> These dishes are usually served with</span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> steamed rice </strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">and are known for their unique and distinctive flavor.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Another popular dish in Mizoram is </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Chak-hao kheer</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">, a </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">traditional dessert made from black rice</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">. The rice is cooked with milk, sugar, and cardamom to create a sweet, creamy pudding. This dish is often served on special occasions, such as weddings and festivals.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mizoram is also known for its variety of smoked meats and fish. These dishes are often prepared using traditional methods, such as smoking over a fire made from bamboo. Smoked meats and fish are often used as ingredients in other dishes or eaten as a snack.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mizoram is also known for its wide variety of local fruits and vegetables. These include a variety of local fruits like oranges, pineapples, and bananas, and vegetables like beans, cucumbers, and different types of leafy greens. These fruits and vegetables are often used in various dishes, both sweet and savory.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The state also has a</span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> strong tea-drinking culture, </strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">with tea being an essential part of daily life. Traditional tea is prepared by brewing tea leaves with ginger and sometimes milk and sugar, which is served in a bamboo cup. The cuisine is a blend of traditional and contemporary flavors, with a strong emphasis on locally sourced ingredients. From bamboo shoot dishes to Chak-hao kheer, from </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">smoked meat and fish </strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">to the variety of fruits and vegetables, from traditional tea to the strong tea-drinking culture, Mizoram has a lot to offer to food enthusiasts.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Also known for its delicious cuisine, which is a blend of Indian and Southeast Asian flavors. Visitors can indulge in traditional Mizo dishes such as bamboo shoots, smoked meat, and fish dishes. The state is also famous for its traditional handloom and handicrafts, which make for great souvenirs.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mizoram is known for its picturesque landscapes, diverse culture, and rich tradition. The state is home to a plethora of tourist destinations, including natural wonders, historical sites, and cultural landmarks. One of the most popular tourist destinations is the </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Durtlang Hills,</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> which offers breathtaking views of the surrounding landscape. The hills are home to a variety of flora and fauna and are a popular spot for trekking and hiking.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Another popular destination is </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Vantawng Falls</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">, which is located in the western part. The falls, which is the highest in the state, are a popular spot for picnics and photography. For those interested in history and culture, the Mizoram State Museum is a must-visit destination. The museum, which is located in the state capital of Aizawl, offers a glimpse into the state\'s rich cultural heritage and history. Visitors can also take a tour of the nearby Solomon\'s Temple, which is an important religious site for the Mizo people.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">For nature lovers, </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">the Phawngpui National Park i</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">s a must-see destination. The park, which is located in the southern part of Mizoram, is home to a variety of flora and fauna, including several rare and endangered species. Visitors can take a guided tour of the park to learn more about the region\'s natural history.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">In addition to the destinations mentioned above, Mizoram is also home to several other tourist attractions, including temples, churches, and a variety of cultural festivals. The state\'s vibrant culture and warm hospitality make it a must-visit destination for anyone looking to experience the best of northeastern India.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Overall, Mizoram offers a unique blend of culture, tradition, and nature that is hard to find elsewhere. From breathtaking natural landscapes to rich cultural heritage, Mizoram has something to offer everyone. And with the state\'s developing tourism infrastructure, it is becoming easier than ever to explore all that this beautiful region has to offer.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">In conclusion, Mizoram is a hidden gem that offers a unique blend of culture, tradition, and adventure. The state\'s tranquil atmosphere, warm hospitality, and diverse culture make it a must-visit destination for anyone looking to experience something different. With its developing tourism infrastructure, it is becoming easier than ever to explore all that Mizoram has to offer.</span></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p>', 'Mizoram Travel Guide: Explore the scenic beauty and rich culture of Northeast India, Discover the hidden gems of Mizoram with our expertly curated travel packages and recommendations, Journey to Mizoram: Your ultimate travel guide to this enchanting land ', 'Mizoram tourism Aizawl city tour Trekking in Mizoram Mizoram culture and traditions Mizo cuisine Mizoram wildlife sanctuaries Mizoram handicrafts Dampa Tiger Reserve Mizoram offbeat destinations Northeast India travel.', '0', '219', 'N/A', 'N/A', '2023-02-27 18:02:47', '2023-02-27 18:02:47');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `category_id`, `title`, `client_type`, `slug`, `image`, `alt`, `summery`, `description`, `meta_title`, `meta_keyword`, `status`, `created_by`, `last_editor`, `published_by`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(134, '32', 'Rajasthan: A state with the most royal culture in history!', 'general', 'rajasthan-a-state-with-the-most-royal-culture-in-history', 'desert-1677521792839196.jpeg', 'desert', 'Discover the vibrant and colorful state of Rajasthan with GB International. From the majestic forts and palaces in Jaipur to the sand dunes of Jaisalmer, this blog takes you on a journey through the rich history and cultural heritage of the desert state. Experience the warm hospitality, indulge in mouth-watering cuisine, and explore the intricate artwork and handicrafts that Rajasthan has to offer.', '<p>Rajasthan, the Maharajahs\' homeland, is known for its diverse culture. But it is the state\'s food that distinguishes it and makes it popular. Rajasthani food, like its culture, is rich, colorful, and distinct. The region\'s aridity, harsh weather conditions, and paucity of water and plants have resulted in the development of distinct culinary methods and eating habits among the locals that are distinct from other Indian cuisines. Rajasthanis have constructed their culinary techniques in such a manner that many of their meals may be stored and served cold for several days. Many local cuisines require milk, a lot of clarified butter, and a lot of native spices. Many Rajasthani cuisines include beans, dry lentils, and legumes including gram flour, bajra, and jowar as primary components. Discover the must-try Rajasthani cuisines, which include a variety of vegetarian and non-vegetarian alternatives as well as sweet and savory treats.</p><p><strong>Mouth-watering delicacies of the Kings land.</strong></p><p>The Land of Kings, Rajasthan, is a synonym for bravery, monarchy, and honor. The state\'s walls are adorned with historic tales of battles won and the romance of wealth. This lovely location, founded in the era of wartime ballads but now thriving in the contemporary day, is a popular tourist attraction. Rajasthan is a must-see destination for anyone searching for historical relics. Wanderers interested in seeing different landscapes should certainly have a look at this adventurous state. Set in a rocky yet attractive backdrop, this region is a colorful jumble of gigantic forts, gorgeous palaces, unique civilizations, wonderful cuisines, and kind people. Rajasthan, India\'s glistening jewel, invites you to discover the eclectic mix of ancient and contemporary. Rajasthan\'s cultural legacy, lively customs, spectacular festivals, mouthwatering cuisine, and majestic history are just a few of the phrases that come to mind when thinking of the country of royalty. With a history dating back over 5000 years. This is a land unlike any other in the world in terms of taste and vitality. Rajasthan\'s dynamic tourism is as appealing as its cultural and artistic legacy, even though it is mostly a desert state. As a result, visitors from all over the world come to this location. If you wish to see the old Indian way of life, Rajasthan should be on your bucket list. From magnificent forts to towering temples to enormous palaces, India has it all savor the splendor of this country. Rajasthan is without a doubt one of India\'s most culturally rich states. The locals wear brilliantly colored clothes known as \"angarakha\" and \"Ghaghara.\" Buttermilk, \"khud khargosh\" (rabbit meat), \"dal baati churma,\" \"gatte ki sabzi,\" and other meals are common in the state\'s cuisine.</p><p><strong>Must have foods when in Rajasthan:</strong></p><p><strong>1. Dal Bati Churma - Rajasthani Traditional Food</strong></p><p>This well-known Rajasthani delicacy needs no introduction. Rajasthani dal bati churma is famous for its crispy batis coated in ghee, as well as spicy daal and sweet churma.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>2. Mohan Thaal</strong></p><p>This regal dessert is as royal in its ability to wow food lovers\' taste senses. Mohan Thaal is a sweet delicacy made with besan and dried fruits that is peculiar to Rajasthan. Ghee\'s scent and flavor are the icings on the cake!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>3. Laal Maas</strong></p><p>The spicy red chiles give Laal Maas its color. The beef is cooked in a spicy sauce made with tomatoes, chilies, and other spices. Don\'t miss out on Rajasthan\'s spicy yet delectable cuisine. Laal maans were traditionally prepared with wild boar or deer. It now consists of a spicy marinated mutton curry cooked on low heat in a hot sauce of red chilies, garlic paste, chopped onions, and curds. For meat-eaters, this is a must-try.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>4. Bajra ki roti with lehsun chutney</strong></p><p>Bajra is a black millet flour that is popular across the state. Thickly rolled bajra rotis are cooked in villages over cow dung cakes, which give the rotis a smoked flavor. Bajra rotis go well with almost every vegetable on the Rajasthani menu. Lasun ki chutney, a garlic dip made with garlic, red chili powder, lime juice, jaggery, and homemade butter, is usually served with bajra roti.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>5.&nbsp;Pyaaz ki kachori </strong></p><p>Pyaaz ki kachori is a common breakfast food that originated in Jodhpur and is now popular throughout the state. They\'re flaky, deep-fried plain flour pieces of bread stuffed with a spicy onion mixture flavored with fennel, cumin, turmeric, and chili powder. Kachoris are typically served with coriander and mint, as well as the date and tamarind chutney.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>6. Ghevar</strong></p><p>A delicious dish from Jaipur that consists of a wheat disc soaked in ghee and milk and topped with chopped almonds. This sweet dish is made in a mould and has a crunchy texture. There are varieties of Ghevar that can be prepared from a plain, mawa (condensed milk), and malai ghevar (cream).</p><p><strong>7. Gatte ki sabzii</strong></p><p>The arid conditions influenced the development of most Rajasthani cuisine. This dish is unique in that it does not require any fresh vegetables. This dish is created with steamed and lightly fried gram flour dumplings with a tangy tomato, buttermilk, and spice sauce. It\'s finest served with rice and rotis (Indian flatbread).&nbsp;</p><p><strong>8. Moong&nbsp;&nbsp;Daal Halwa</strong></p><p>Moong Dal Halwas are a popular dessert in Rajasthan during the winter months, and this dish frequently appears on royal wedding menus. Moong ki Daal ka Halwa is made using moong dal and topped with a variety of dried fruits. Every mouthful is infused with a savory flavor</p><p><strong>9. Malpua</strong></p><p>Malpuas are another traditional Rajasthani dessert. This delectable dish is made with flour, milk, khoya, and dried fruits. Rabdi with Malpua is one of the complimentary dishes. Malpuas from Pushkar is well-known, particularly during Makar Sankranti</p><p><strong>10. Masala-Chhach</strong></p><p>Buttermilk, or chhach, is an essential element of Rajasthani cuisine. In the state\'s desert environment and adverse weather conditions, chhach is a must-have. Masala Chhach is a delicious drink that is typically served with breakfasts and meals. The drink may be consumed independently of the main dish and is ideal for hot summer days.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>11. Kadhi</strong></p><p>&nbsp;Kadhi is the most popular but versatile Indian dish. Rajasthani kadhi, which is often cooked with besan pakodis, is spicier and more delicious. This is Rajasthan\'s most well-known dish.</p><p><strong>12. Mirchi Bada</strong></p><p>Mirchi badas, another Rajasthani delicacy, are the ideal accompaniment to evening tea or early breakfast. The hot and spicy badas are very delectable.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>13. Mohan Maas</strong></p><p>Mohan maas is a finely prepared beef dish that is another regal component of the non-vegetarian plate. Mohan maas is a rajwadi variant of non-veg pleasures, stuffed with dried fruits and cooked in milk and cream before being decorated with cardamom and cinnamon.</p><p><strong>14. Boondi Raita</strong></p><p>Due to the wildness of the flavours and spices, every Rajasthani dish requires a stabiliser. Instead of reaching for a glass of water, it\'s time to reach for a glass of Boondi Raita. Boondi is a tasty, healthful combination of little fried chickpea flour balls dipped in yoghurt and fresh mint. It will elevate your appreciation of all Rajasthani foods!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>15. Badam Halwa</strong></p><p>For all those with a sweet craving, it\'s time to savour the richness of Badam ka Halwa, Rajasthan\'s hallmark sweet delicacy. This meal is sure to leave you wanting for another hot serve, thanks to the royal touch of soaked almonds, crushed and simmered in fineness of desi ghee. It\'s quite addictive. And it\'s also good for you!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>With this, we come to an end of the food angle, though the number of amazing food delicacies you can find in Rajasthan is a never-ending list for a short trip, these are your must-haves.</p><p>Now we move forward to some<strong> must-do things</strong> that you can just not avoid if youre in Rajasthan. </p><p><strong>Things you have to do if you are in the Desert City</strong></p><p><strong>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Safari  A Rendezvous With Rajasthan\'s Wildlife: </p><p>Rajasthan is home to some of India\'s top wildlife and bird reserves. Ranthambore National Park, Sariska Tiger Reserve, Keoladeo National Park, and Bharatpur Bird Sanctuary are among the most popular. Tigers, elephants, boars, bears, a variety of bird species, and other wild animals welcome you to these wildlife preserves.Wear clean clothes, don\'t litter, and avoid wearing strong perfumes.</p><p>Hours: 7 a.m. to 3 p.m.</p><p>There is no entry cost.</p><p><strong>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Zip Lining  Go Zip Lining From One Cliff To Another:&nbsp;</p><p>Zip Lining, or Flying Fox as it is also called, is one of the most popular activities in Rajasthan. Go whizzing from one cliff or structure to the next, taking in the breathtaking views of forts along the route. In Rajasthan, zip lining is available at Neemrana Fort and Mehrangarh Fort. While both have beautiful vistas, Neemrana is a great place to visit near Delhi, and Mehrangarh is close to Udaipur.</p><p>9 a.m. to 5 p.m. for Zipline (Mehrangarh Fort).</p><p>Make sure you\'re wearing a helmet and that the full body harness is comfortable for you.</p><p>NO ENTRY FEE</p><p><strong>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Float In The Sky With Hot-Air Ballooning: </p><p>Hot-air ballooning is one of Rajasthan\'s most thrilling sports, and it\'s a big hit with visitors and travellers. From the heights of the sky, you can see the intricate details of heritage architecture as well as vast expanses of greenery. The experience is fantastic and gives you a glimpse into this magnificent area. Pushkar, Jaipur, and Ranthambore are the three cities in Rajasthan where you may go hot-air ballooning right now. Choose your favourite scenery and begin your journey through the sky. If you\'ve ever wondered what to do in Rajasthan, here you know.</p><p>Make sure you\'re in good shape before embarking on this adventure.</p><p>Timetable: 10 a.m. to 6.30 p.m.</p><p>There is no entry cost.</p><p><strong>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Feel the Rush of Desert Camping: </p><p>This fantastic glamping spot is well-known for its desert camping. Camping in Rajasthan is popular because of the starry sky, lively folk dances, vivid puppet performances, excellent authentic dinners, and cosy beddings. This incredible desert camping experience is undoubtedly one of the best things to do in Rajasthan during the winter months.</p><p>Avoid going during the summer because of the intense heat.</p><p>Time limit: 24 hours Fee: NA</p><p><strong>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Chokhi Dhani - Get A Real Rajasthani Taste</p><p>Chokhi Dhani, one of the best sites to visit in Rajasthan, requires no introduction. Chokhi Dhani, a name synonymous with regal hospitality, has catered to ardent tourists and hungry foodies for many years.</p><p>Chokhi Dhani delivers traditional Rajasthani cuisine with a warm welcome. Even if you don\'t like Rajasthani cuisine, the service and atmosphere will leave you speechless. To say the least, the cultural displays and colorful folk dances are captivating. When making a list of activities to do in Rajasthan, don\'t forget to include this one.</p><p>5.30 p.m. to 11:00 p.m.</p><p>A two-person lunch costs: 1,600 INR</p><p>Tip: ask the chef about the Rajasthani items and try all of them</p><p><strong>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Rajasthan Vintage Car Rally - For Car Enthusiasts</p><p>This doesn\'t require any further explanation at this point. Surely, some of you were sold only on the basis of a \'Vintage Car.\' For the remainder, these rallies are the greatest time to see Rajasthan\'s luxury, especially in Jaipur. The gorgeous streets are taken over by these magnificent cars, and it is pure joy for car enthusiasts to simply watch the rally. For fans of mean machines, it is undoubtedly one of the best things to do in Rajasthan. It happens every year in January and is undoubtedly a once-in-a-lifetime experience.</p><p>NA (not available)</p><p>There is no entry cost.</p><p>Check the timings ahead of time.</p><p><strong>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Admire the Stunning Architecture at Abhaneri Step Well:</p><p>Abhaneri Step Well, or Chand Baori as it is more well known, is a brilliant light in the Dausa District near Jaipur\'s cultural exhibit. Visiting the imperial edifice and admiring its architecture and splendour is one of the top things to do in Rajasthan. The historic landmark, which was formerly used to collect rainwater, astonishes with its sheer magnificence and massive size. Are you still undecided on what to see and do in Rajasthan? We have a lot more listings, so don\'t worry.</p><p>Hours: 8 a.m. to 6 p.m.</p><p>There is no entry cost.</p><p>Keep your eyes peeled and don\'t fall.</p><p><strong>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Trekking:</p><p>Given the scorching summer temperature, trekking in Rajasthan can be difficult and exhausting. It can be a fantastic experience in the right season and on a little windy day. For adventure seekers, the lush nature of Alwar and the heritage density of Mount Abu are the most popular climbs. While these hikes range in difficulty from easy to moderate, the otherworldly beauty and pleasant environment draw not just adventurers but also nature enthusiasts. You\'ll be able to see a variety of birds and connect with the locals. This should be on your list of things to do in Rajasthan.</p><p>Tip: Bring a map and do some research on the location ahead of time.</p><p>Timing: It is open, but it is recommended that you hike between the hours of 5 a.m. and 6 p.m.</p><p>There is no entry cost.</p><p><strong>9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Befriend the \"Ships of the Desert\" at a camel breeding farm near Bikaner.</p><p>Befriending camels is one of the most strange but fascinating things to do in Rajasthan. Try petting and playing with camels at the Camel Breeding Farm in Bikaner. A journey here could be the highlight of your holiday, especially if you\'re travelling with children.</p><p>Time: 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.</p><p>Fee: not applicable</p><p>Try their fresh ice cream produced with camel\'s milk as a tip.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>10.</strong>Allow The Adrenaline Rush To Take Over When Dune Bashing:</p><p>Dune bashing is a popular activity in the Thar Desert, and it\'s a genuine adrenaline rush. It\'s thrilling to drive an SUV through the vast desert. Don\'t worry if you don\'t own an SUV. You can hire one from a local vendor and have a great time.</p><p>If you own the vehicle, there is no fee.</p><p>Tip: If possible, plan your vacation for the winter and bring a camera, hat, sunglasses, and plenty of water.</p><p>Hours: 8 a.m. to 12 p.m.</p><p><strong>11.</strong>Dera Amer Elephants - A Day With Elephants:</p><p>Have you ever spent a day in the company of elephants? Well, now is the ideal time to have one. You can participate in a variety of elephant-related activities, such as giving them a bath or feeding them sugarcane. You may also use organic colors to paint their trunks so they don\'t get hurt. It is one of the most popular tourist destinations in the Jaipur area. You can also eat real Rajasthani cuisine on the spot while enjoying your day at Dera Amer. If you\'ve gotten your fill for the day, go for a short hike into the neighboring woodland on a nature trail.</p><p>Fee: INR 6800 for an evening with an elephant and dinner.</p><p><strong>12.</strong>One of the most popular activities is a camel safari:</p><p>A camel safari in Rajasthan is another one of the unique exexperiencevailable. Views of the desert from a camel\'s back are much more stunning. The desert ship allows you to explore the ruins and stunning architecture from an unrivalled vantage point. Pushkar and Jaisalmer are the greatest cities in Rajasthan to go on a camel safari.</p><p>Time: 8 am to 4:30 pm</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>13.</strong>Match The Steps To The Music Of The Kalbeliya Trib:</p><p>It\'s a joy to see the Kalbeliya Tribe\'s hypnotising traditional dance performance. Enjoy the exquisite dance performances by the tribe\'s attractive women, and I\'m sure their belly dancing skills will wow you. When visiting the \"Land of Maharajas\" with your family and friends, don\'t miss this beautiful folk dance performance. Make sure this is on your list of things to do in Rajasthan.</p><p><strong>14.</strong>Create Waves With A Motor Boat On Fateh Sagar Lake:</p><p>Speed boating in Udaipur\'s Fateh Sagar Lake is another exciting thing to do in Rajasthan. Aside from the thrills and excitement, the gorgeous view over the lake and the setting sun behind the mountains (in the evening) is a treat!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hours: 8 a.m. to 4.30 p.m.</p><p>Entry fee: Nil; Regular boat rise  INR 30 and motor boat ride  INR 200</p><p><strong>15.</strong>Pushkar Horse Safari - Take In The Royal City:</p><p>The regal state, the regal manners! What better way to experience the royal city of Pushkar than on horseback? The horses will carry you through rural roads and elegant alleys while you take in the breathtaking scenery. This is an opportunity not to be missed.</p><p>Hours: 8 a.m. to 4.30 p.m.</p><p>There is no entry fee; INR 30 for a regular boat ride; INR 200 for a motor boat ride</p><p><strong>16.</strong>Cycling Through Jaipur - Peddle Your Way around The Pink City:</p><p>One of the nicest things to do in Rajasthan is to go scavenging in Jaipur. Many organisers lead groups on cycling excursions of the city and the surrounding countryside. The length and number of pit stops are determined by the operator. However, these tours can be tailored to suit your needs in terms of duration and pit stops.</p><p>Time: 5 a.m. to 6 p.m.</p><p>There is no entry cost.</p><p><strong>17.</strong>Reach For The Sky At The Kite Festival:</p><p>This is an interesting activity to do in Rajasthan if you happen to come during Makar Sankranti, which occurs on January 14th. Thousands of colourful kites flutter through the air during Jodhpur\'s annual Kite Festival. Now that the festival has garnered international acclaim, it attracts a large number of foreign tourists and kite enthusiasts. Also, while you\'re in town, don\'t forget to check out the top sites to see in Jodhpur.</p><p>Hours: 8 a.m. to 6:30 p.m.</p><p>There is no entry cost.</p><p>Tip: When flying kites, be careful not to cut your fingers because the thread is very sharp.</p><p><strong>18.</strong>Encounter With Ghosts at Bhangarh Fort: </p><p>Have you had your fill of beauty? Let\'s add a dash of horror right now! The remains and buildings of Bhangarh Fort are stunning, but the stories surrounding them are terrifying. Bhangarh is the most daring thing you can do in Rajasthan. While the evenings of Bhangarh are supposed to be the most terrifying, some claim that the days are just as frightening.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hours: 6 a.m. to 6 p.m.</p><p>Entry fee: nil; camera fee: INR 25 Tip: don\'t trust rumours</p><p><strong>19.</strong>Say Your Prayers at Ajmer Sharif:</p><p>Ajmer Sharif, one of Rajasthan\'s most popular tourist destinations, is the hallowed resting place of Sufi Saint Moinuddin Chishti. Thousands of believers visit the temple every day. With trusting hearts, fervent believers of all religions flock to the majestic dargah, which is known for its spell of granting and fulfilling all wishes. For all those seeking peace, visiting this area and praying is one of the things to do in Rajasthan. This is one of the spots in Rajasthan that you must see to fully appreciate its significance.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Summer hours are 4 a.m. to 10 p.m., while winter hours are 5 a.m. to 9 p.m.</p><p>There is no entry cost.</p><p>Wear something on your head as a tip.</p><p><strong>20.</strong>Rajasthan\'s Rural Pockets - Discover Village Life: </p><p>Have you had your fill of beauty? Let\'s add a dash of horror right now! The remains and buildings of Bhangarh Fort are stunning, but the stories surrounding them are terrifying. Bhangarh is the most daring thing you can do in Rajasthan. While the evenings of Bhangarh are supposed to be the most terrifying, some claim that the days are just as frightening.</p><p>Hours: 6 a.m. to 6 p.m.</p><p>Entry fee: nil; camera fee: INR 25 Tip: don\'t trust rumours</p><p><strong>So many beautiful locations wanting your attention in the Desert state.</strong></p><p>There are various factors that contribute to Rajasthan\'s uniqueness. The area is known for its opulent forts and palaces that exude regal opulence. Aside from that, the state has a number of step wells, baoris, and temples. As a result, a trip to Rajasthan must include these prominent destinations.</p><p>Now let us move toward the enigmatic grandeur that Rajasthan cities have to offer. Following are some of the must visit cities in Rajasthan. Starting with the city of:</p><p><strong>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Alwar</strong></p><p>Visiting Alwar is like traveling through time. The city, set in the Aravalli range, features countless historical jewels from the time when it was one of Rajasthan\'s oldest and richest kingdoms, from a stately fort and palaces to a wildlife sanctuary that was formerly the royal hunting grounds.</p><p>The city\'s focal point is the massive Bala Qila, which appears to be a great monument. The fort is an excellent vantage point for seeing panoramic views of the city, with six majestic gates and exquisite architecture. Another attraction is the Sariska Wildlife Sanctuary, which used to be the maharaja\'s hunting reserve. The sanctuary is home to a large population of tigers, chital, nilgai, sambar, and other animals, as well as remnants of old forts and temples with sculptures similar to those found at Khajuraho.</p><p>Alwar is mentioned in the Mahabharata epic, and it is thought to be the location where the Pandavas brothers spent part of their exile. In 1500 BC, Alwar was supposed to have been a component of Viratnagar\'s Matsya domains. Furthermore, during the Mughal Empire, the area was vital since it served as a base for attacking neighbouring kingdoms. The Jat king of Bharatpur later captured it. In 1775, however, Pratap Singh of Machheri took it from the Jats and declared it a sovereign state.</p><p><strong>Places to visit in Alwar:</strong></p><p>The massive <strong>Bala Qila fort</strong>, nestled in the Aravalli hills, is nothing short of a majestic monument. The fort, which is positioned at a height of 300 meters, was built as the city\'s protector by Hasan Khan Mewati, the Rajput prince of Mewat, in the 15th century. The building is well defended and has marble columns and beautiful latticed balconies. The fort\'s six big gates, Pol, Suraj Pol, Laxman Pol, Chand Pol, Krishan Pol, and Andheri Gate, provide an idea of its scale. Tourists today ascend to the top of the fort for panoramic views of Alwar. During its golden days, the Bala Qila, or youthful power centre that was passed down through dynasties like the Yadavas, Marathas, and Kachwaha Rajputs that wanted to govern the region. In reality, after capturing the fort in 1775, the Kachwahas lay the groundwork for the city of Alwar. It is a gem since it is one of the few forts erected in the state before the Mughals arrived. Babur and Akbar, Mughal rulers, are reported to have resided here.</p><p>The fort now houses a radio transmitter station, and only a few areas are open to the public with permission from the Superintendent of Police in the City Palace Complex.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Jodhpur</strong></p><p>The architectural marvel of Jodhpur, Rajasthan\'s second-largest city, is a sea of sapphire-blue painted buildings surrounded by the beautiful Mehrangarh Fort. A maze of ancient passageways, interspersed with bustling marketplaces, crisscross the city, which has a leisurely pace of life. Head to the city\'s busy bazaars to see spiritual Pichwai paintings, Jodhpuri pants or breeches, elegant bandini or bandhej (tie and dye) sarees, stunning badla embroidered lehengas, and morchang, a traditional Rajasthani folk music instrument.&nbsp;The city has a vibrant culinary scene, and experiencing local specialties such as savory pyaz-ki-kachori, spicy Mirchi bada, and thick and sweet makhaniya lassi is a memorable experience. As you explore further, Jodhpur enchants you with its rich royal past, which can be seen in buildings such as the sumptuous Umaid Bhawan Palace, the towering Jaswant Thada, and the picturesque Mandore Gardens, which were all erected by the city\'s former rulers. The old and contemporary sides of the city are separated by a 10-kilometer-long wall with eight massive gates, allowing travelers to see the distinctive aspects of Jodhpur\'s historical past rubbing elbows with its cosmopolitan present.</p><p><strong>Places to visit:</strong></p><p>Khichan Village, which is a popular stopover for migrating birds, for a real Rajasthani rural life experience. When the arid temperatures drop and birds glide over the clear water of the Khichan Bird Sanctuary, the evenings here are pure delight. </p><p>Rao Jodha, the Rathore clan\'s leader, built Jodhpur in 1459. It appeals to a wide spectrum of interests and inclinations, making it one of the country\'s most popular tourist sites.</p><p>Mehrangarh Fort is one of the greatest forts of Jodhpur. Jaswant Thada is a beautiful white marble fort known as the second Taj Mahal. Toorji Ka Jhalra is a step well which was a common thing for the cities of Rajasthan in old times to store water. Umaid Bhawan Palace, a huge and grand palace that is a must-visit. Sardar Market, Ghanta Ghar, Mandore Garden, Phool Mahal, Balsamand Lake, and Garden</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Jaipur</strong></p><p>If you\'re starting your Rajasthan tour in Jaipur, you\'re in for a wonderful treat because this is where your journey into India truly begins!</p><p>Although it is known as the \"pink city,\" it isn\'t actually pink. The colour of the buildings is actually peach. Nonetheless, it\'s quite lovely. Jaipur, the capital of Rajasthan, is a vibrant, buzzing city with a mix of old and new architecture. Although the ancient side has more culture, the modern side also includes some 21st-century conveniences such as shopping malls, bars, and clubs. Finding your way about Jaipur might be a bit of a maze, so here\'s a helpful Jaipur travel guide for first-timers.</p><p><strong>Places to visit in Jaipur</strong></p><p>Forts: Nahargarh Fort, Jaigarh Fort, Bhangarh Fort, Achrol Fort, Amer Fort</p><p>Palaces:&nbsp;Hawa Maha, City Palace Rambagh Palace Jantar MantarAmer Fort Jal Mahal</p><p>Temples: Galtaji, Govind Devji Temple, Bhuteshwar Nath Mahadev, Moti Dungri Temple, Akshardham Temple, Garh Ganesh Temple, Digamber Jain Mandir Sanghiji, Khole Ke Hanuman Ji Temple.</p><p>Tourist attractions: Albert Hall Museum, Sisodia Rani Garden, Central Park, Ram Nivas Garden, Kanak Vrindavan Garden, Chokhi Dhani, Panna Meena Ka Kund, Sambhar Lake, Hathni Kund, Chour Ghati, Water Valley, Jhalana Leopard Conservation Reserve</p><p>Markets: Johari Bazaar, Bapu Bazaar, Indira Bazaar, Sanjay Bazaar, Mirza Ismail Road, Tripolia Bazaar, Chandpole, Ramganj Bazaar</p><p>Night life and cafes: Bar Palladio, Shikaar Bagh, Forresta, blackout, G Club, Club trove, House of People, C-Scheme</p><p><strong>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Udaipur</strong></p><p>With its breathtaking forts, beautiful lakes, and centuries of interwoven culture and history, this city is surely one of the nicest parts of Rajasthan.</p><p>According to ancient Indian history, the city of Udaipur served as the capital of the erstwhile Kingdom of Mewar. Mewar is a hilly and lushly green region of Rajasthan. It is located on the windward side of the enormous Aravallis, one of the world\'s oldest mountains. Many people may tell you that Udaipur is too \'touristy\' and crowded, yet we recommend that you include Udaipur in your schedule. Especially if you enjoy history and are interested in learning about Rajasthan\'s distinct culture. This city in Rajasthan is continually attracting visitors from India and throughout the world. In fact, the royal city is a renowned tourist attraction for visitors from throughout the world. Many superstars from Hollywood and Bollywood have opted to exchange vows by the glistening Lake Pichola. Udaipur is also a cultural and artistic hotspot. </p><p><strong>Take a look at these beautiful places to visit in Udaipur:</strong></p><p>Lake Palace, City Palace Jag Mandir The Monsoon Palace Ahar Cenotaphs, Fateh Sagar Lake, Kumbhalgarh Fort, Saheliyon Ki Bari, Bhartiya Lok, Kala Museum, Shilpgram Bagore Ki Haveli, Bhartiya Lok Kala Museum, Shilpgram Vintage Car Museum, Lake Pichola, Karni Mata Temple, Jawahar Nagar, Jagat Niwas, Hathi Pol Bazaar, Ambrai Amet Haveli, Mistri Jaiwana Haveli, Raas Leela Doodh Talai Musical Garden, Sukhadia Circle, Eklingji Temple, Jagdish Temple, Maharana Pratap Memorial, Udaipur Solar Observatory, Crystal Gallery, Charcoal By Carlson, Sheesh Mahal, Chetak Circle, Jaisamand Lake, Haldighati, Chittorgarh Fort, Badi Lake, Bada Bazaar Gangaur Ghat, Rajasthali Nathdwara Temple, Bapu Bazaar, Mewar Biodiversity Park, Marvel Water Park, Aravali Nature View, Udaipur Ghat.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ajmer</strong></p><p>Consider travelling on a Thursday night for a destination known for its royalness and history. Rajasthan\'s cities and towns each have their own distinct vibe. The ever-bustling city of Ajmer is one such example. This city not only has a lot to offer on its own, but it is also surrounded by many beautiful places to visit. The picturesque city of Ajmer in Rajasthan, surrounded by the Aravalli Hills, is a haven for all types of travellers, especially those seeking calm. There are numerous things to do in Ajmer, and we can attest that every experience here is absolutely soul-satisfying, whether it\'s simply relaxing by the lake or learning about the city\'s history. While visiting the holy Dargah is undoubtedly a must-do in the city, there are other other great experiences to be had for an enriching stay in Rajasthan.</p><p>Below are <strong>places you can visit and things you can do in Ajmer:</strong></p><p>Ajmer Sharif Dargah  Seek Blessings, Ana Sagar Lake  Go Boating, Learn the Legends of Adhai Din Ka Jhonpra, Jain Temples  Visit, Daulat Bagh  Take A Peaceful Stroll, Akbar Palace and Museum  Witness Its Grandeur, Lake Jagat Palace - Stay Like a Royalty Admire,The Beautiful Sunset At Foy Sagar, Bazaars in the Neighborhood - Go Shopping, Participate in the Pushkar Camel Fair, Take a look at the architecture at Mayo College, Pay Your Respects - Soniji Ki Nasiyan, Explore Taragarh Fort!, Enjoy the nightlife at Sipah Salar Bar.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pushkar</strong></p><p>Pushkar is a charming tiny town that provides visitors with a memorable experience. Some of the best things to do in Pushkar include an amazing climb, a magnificent temple, hot air balloon rides, camel rides, and rooftop cafes. Pushkar, a culturally rich town in Ajmer, Rajasthan, is known for its old temples, fascinating streets, bustling bazaars, and magnificent ghats, as well as its history, culture, tales, and adventures. The best things to do in Pushkar are highly diverse, making it a popular vacation for individuals of all tastes. You won\'t have to worry about what to do in Pushkar during your trip because the best things to do in Pushkar are extremely diverse. There\'s so much to do and see in Pushkar, from hot air ballooning to jeep safaris, from souvenir shopping to sampling local cuisine. </p><p>Below are <strong>places you can visit and things you can do in Pushkar:</strong></p><p>Jeep Safari is an exhilarating experience, A Camel Safari That Is Both Bumpy And Exciting, Prepare for a Desert Camping Trip, In The Sky, Take A Ride In A Hot Air Balloon, Trekking to Ratnagiri Hill, hiking to Pap Mochani Temple, driving to Ajaypal Ji, and taking a cable ride to Savitri Temple. Bazaars are great places to go shopping for handicrafts. Local Street Food and Unique Restaurants are worth a try. Merta, an ancient city, is worth a visit.</p><p>In Pushkar Lake, take a holy bath. Spend A Day At The Yoga Garden In Pushkar</p><p>Take Nagara Lessons At Gangaur Ghat and Visit The Rose Garden, Observe a Kalbelia Dance Performance in Real Time</p><p><strong>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Jaisalmer</strong></p><p>The Golden City of Jaisalmer was once a tranquil desert that has now turned into a major tourist destination with visitors from all over the world coming to it. Jaisalmer, often known as \'The Sun City,\' is located in the picturesque Thar Desert and is named for Maharawal Jaisal Singh, the city\'s founder. The yellow sandstone and sand provide an ideal setting for relaxation and exploration of Jaisalmer\'s various characteristics as they progress. Camping in a tent in the intriguing Thar desert is a must-do while you\'re here. From the majesty of the Thar Desert to the allure of royal forts and palaces, these finest places to see in Jaisalmer in December will keep you entertained. The weather in Jaisalmer is as beautiful as favourable as it can be, welcoming visitors with open arms. Jaisalmer is a paradise, with the sun shining brightly during the day and a cool breeze rising the hair on the skin during the night. Furthermore, Jaisalmer offers a wide range of activities and sights to see, and the pleasant weather just enhances an already exceptional experience.</p><p>The best time to visit Jaisalmer is from November to March. These months provide pleasant weather for desert safaris. Tourists from all over the world flock to the bright desert event in February. <strong>Check out the fun list of things to do in Jaisalmer provided below:</strong></p><p>The Grandeur of Jaisalmer Fort, Observe the Scenic Beauty of Jaisalmer City, Enjoy The View At Gadisar Lake, Local Bazaar of Jaisalmer  Shopping, Parasailing in Kanol, Embark on an adventure with paramotoring, Quad Biking at Sam Sand Dunes, Dune Bashing in the Thar Desert, Desert Safari And Camping At Winds Desert Camp, Tanot Mata Temple is located on the Indo-Pak border, Observe the wildlife in the Desert National Park, Puppet Show at the Desert Culture Centre and Museum, Experiencing Rajasthani Cuisine for the First Time, Desert Jeep Safari  An Exciting Adventure, A Camel Safari is a Unique Adventure, Salim Singh Ki Haveli is a magnificent sight to behold, tour of a Jain Temple | Awe-Inspiring Architecture, Marvel At The Architecture Of Nathmal Ki Haveli, Visit the Abandoned Village in Kuldhara, explore the heritage of Khaba Fort, and watch the sunset at Vyas Chhatri Suryagarh - Have Dinner in the Sand Dunes, Experience The Festivities At The Jaisalmer Desert Festival Indo-Pak Border  Take A Look At The Other Side, Local Cuisine: Satisfy Your Inner Foodie, arty Until You Drop is the motto of the nightlife, Jaisalmer Nightwalk Tour: Night Sky Views, An Entertaining Puppet Show, Rooftop Dining: For A Special Evening, Rajasthan Cultural Tour: An Unforgettable Experience, For Your Instagram, Take a Photo Tour, An Overnight Adventure in the Sand Dunes, Lodurva is a historical relic worth seeing, A Glorious Showcase of Light and Sound</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mount Abu</strong></p><p>The Scenic Hill Station of Mount Abu billed as Rajasthan\'s lone hill station, is a popular tourist destination thanks to its laid-back ambiance and lush green environs. The most important attractions, however, are the Dilwara temples, which are among the most beautiful architectural structures in the country. If you are interested in history, this is one of the destinations in India that you should not miss. Mount Abu is a beautiful hill station in Rajasthan, India, lying at an elevation of 1220 metres above sea level. It is the only hill station in the royal state of Rajasthan. Mount Abu is surrounded by densely forested Aravali hills, and even the highest mountain in the Aravalli Ranges, Guru Shikhar, is located there. The natural riches of rivers, lakes, waterfalls, and evergreen woods abound on this slope. It is a charming oasis amid the sandy deserts of Rajasthan that has kept India\'s glorious cultural history for decades. It is also interesting to note that it is popularly thought to be the birthplace of India\'s first Rajput (ruling clan). <strong>Check out the fun list of things to do in Mount Abu provided below:</strong></p><p>Dilwara temple, Achalgarh Fort, Nakki Lake<strong>, </strong><strong style=\"color: black;\">Peace Park, Mount Abu Wildlife Sanctuary, Guru Shikhar Peak, Sunset Point, </strong>&nbsp;Abu Road, Trevors Tank Toad Rocke Sri Raghunath Temple Honeymoon Point Tibetan Market Adhar Devi Temple Universal Peace Hall Gaumukh Temple Mt Abu Bazaar Arbuda Devi Brahma Kumaris Spiritual University Sirohi Ranakpur Jessore Sloth Bear Sanctuary Nathdwara Jawai Ambaji Temple</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rajasthan is a state full of culture and before spending your marvelous trip here. Keep these things in mind for a wonderful trip!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Keywords </strong></p><p>History of Rajasthan </p><p>Rajasthan culture</p><p>Desert state</p><p>Famous rajasthani food</p><p>Top Rajasthani foods</p><p>Places to visit in Rajasthan</p><p>Tourist destinations of Rajasthan</p><p>Famous places in Rajasthan</p><p>Things to do in Rajasthan</p><p>Safari in Rajasthan</p><p>Pink city</p><p>Blue city</p><p>First planned city</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"color: black;\">&nbsp;</span></p>', 'Discover the Royal History of Rajasthan: A Complete Travel Guide, Rajasthan: A Land of Forts, Palaces, and Rich Cultural Heritage, Experience the Magic of Rajasthan: Travel Tips and Must-See Destinations, Rajasthan: The Land of Vibrant Colors and Rich Tra', 'Rajasthan tourism Jaipur city tour Jodhpur fort Udaipur lake city Jaisalmer desert safari Rajasthan cultural experiences Mount Abu hill station Ranthambore National Park Rajasthan handicrafts Pushkar camel fair Rajasthan offbeat destinations Hawa Mahal Rajasthan cuisine Mehrangarh Fort Rajasthan architecture Rajasthan heritage hotels Bikaner food tour Shekhawati region Rajasthan folk music Rajasthani traditional outfits.', '0', '219', 'N/A', 'N/A', '2023-02-27 18:16:32', '2023-02-27 18:16:32');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `category_id`, `title`, `client_type`, `slug`, `image`, `alt`, `summery`, `description`, `meta_title`, `meta_keyword`, `status`, `created_by`, `last_editor`, `published_by`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(135, '33', 'Offbeat destinations in Madhya Pradesh: Uncovering the state\'s hidden treasures', 'general', 'offbeat-destinations-in-madhya-pradesh-uncovering-the-states-hidden-treasures', 'madhya-pradesh-1677522537369673.octet-stream', 'madhya pradesh', 'Explore the heart of India with our Madhya Pradesh travel guide. From the world-renowned temples of Khajuraho and the wildlife of Bandhavgarh National Park to the historic city of Gwalior and the tranquil beauty of Pachmarhi, there is something for everyone in this fascinating state. Let GB International take you on an unforgettable journey through the heartland of India.', '<p><strong>To know a place, dive into its history and culture</strong></p><p>The place where every childs friend, MOWGLI was born, the land where tigers and leopards roam is a heaven for all nature enthusiasts and a must-visit for an amazing vacation. It has some of India\'s densest forest cover and <strong>Mowgli\'s home</strong>. That is Madhya Pradesh, the country\'s lush green heart!</p><p>A state abundant in forests has been increasing its green cover and is a refuge for seeing animals. It is home to a significant <strong>Hindu, Jain, and Buddhist</strong> cultural legacy. And also incredibly rich in architecture, with countless monuments, well-carved caverns, forts, palaces, and other historical sites. Madhya Pradesh is a whirlpool that continuously connects the several facets of its multifaceted culture and upholds a gorgeously integrated legacy with a distinct zeal culture because it is situated in the geographic center of the nation.</p><p>The diverse cultural mosaic includes several lively tribes, the <strong>Bhils, Gonds, Oraons, Kols, Bhilalas, Murias, and Korkens</strong>, to mention a few. </p><p>In 1956, Madhya Pradesh became a state of India. Modern-day Madhya Pradesh was created when Chhattisgarh was split in half in 2000. With some of the best cuisines and architectural miracles, it has so much to offer! So let us dive into it.</p><p><strong>Mesmerizing Deccan food of India!</strong></p><p>Offering a wide variety of tantalizing foods, Madhya Pradesh\'s cuisine differs depending on the location and has been affected by its bordering states. The use of rich oil and well-known Indian spices in meals is due to the state\'s history with Maharajas and Nawabs is evident. Here is a list of some excellent meals you must try while visiting. </p><p><strong>1. Poha</strong></p><p>Poha is a dish that can be found all throughout the country, but none compares to the version made in Madhya Pradesh. For the ideal palate treat, combine the delicious treat with sweet jalebis. Savor the delectable Poha as you begin your holiday.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>2.&nbsp;Dal Bafla</strong></p><p>The Dal Bafla was influenced by Rajasthan\'s enticing Dal Baati. The distinction between the two dishes is in the churma; Dal Bafla is served with baingan ka bharta in desi ghee. One of Madhya Pradesh\'s delectable meals with hot dal, the cooked wheat dough is enjoyed. You shouldn\'t forgo the delicacy since the flavor combination tickles your taste senses. </p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>3. Gosht Korma from Bhopal</strong></p><p>The Bhopali Gosht Korma is a kid of Mughlai influence that exists to make people fall in love with its taste. It is typically served at banquets and jashans and is a royal meal of Maharajas and Rajas. This Nawabi meal is produced by slowly simmering chunks of mutton in a flavorful stew that will have you craving more. Enjoy it with rumali roti. If you want to try this wonderful meat recipe, go to Bhopal\'s tiny food market Chatori Gali, which is renowned for its Nawabi specialties.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>4. Seekh Kebab</strong></p><p>Coal is used to grill these delicious kebabs. You can eat them as appetizers or as snacks before dinner!</p><p>Seekh Kebab is another product of Mughal cuisine. While visiting Madhya Pradesh, one must try them. It is made by skewering minced meat and cooking it over coals, which makes it more flavorful and melt-in-your-mouth. On Seekh, it is nicely garnished with chutney and given on festive occasions and special occasions. Go to Bhopal if you want to eat the greatest Seekh Kebabs.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>5. Mawa Baati</strong></p><p>Mawa Baati is a fantastic and exceptional sweet treat. Created with mawa dough that has been rolled into balls after being combined with rich dry fruits. These balls are then dipped in sugar syrup, deep-fried, and decorated with coconut powder. It is offered during celebratory events and resembles a huge gulab jamun. If you enjoy sweets and are on vacation in Madhya Pradesh, you must taste this mouthwatering treat, which is sold in practically all eateries and sweet stores, particularly the street food vendors. Among the few additional foods from Madhya Pradesh that can readily satiate your sweet craving are Srikhand, Imarti, Faluda, Kaju Katli, Lavang Lata, and Rabri.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>6. Indori Namkeen </strong></p><p><em>Indore aake namkeen naa khaaye toh kya khaaye. </em>If here, you have t try this. Frequently used as a garnish on dishes like poha, sev puri, bhel puri, etc. The largest selection of Namkeens is found in Indore include Dalmoth, Phalhari Potato Chiwra, Khatta Metha Chiwra, and Khasta Kachori. A wide variety of delicious namkeens, including uncommon flavors like pineapple sev and pani puri sev, are sold by Ganesh Namkeen in Indore\'s Sarafa Market. The khatta meetha Indori namkeen is one particular kind that is quite well-liked.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>7. Shahi Shikanji </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This is not your everyday lemonade, NO. Shahi Shikanji primarily consists of milk, dahi, and dry fruit in place of lemon. Milk is combined with cardamom and saffron. You are in for a treat with the first sip since the combination of shrikhand, rabdi, milk, and dry fruits will tempt you. Saffron, cardamom powder, and dry fruits like cashew nuts, raisins, almonds, and pistachios are used to improve the flavor and taste. It comes in a variety of tastes, including mango and Gulab.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>8. Biryani Pilaf</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Mutton and basmati rice are the main ingredients of the Madhya Pradesh specialty meal known as Biryani Pilaf, also known as Mutton Palav. The Zarda, a sweet dessert comprised of rice, sugar, and milk that is spiced with raisins, pistachios, almonds, cardamom, and saffron to give even more taste, is served alongside this dish. When visiting Madhya Pradesh, you must try this; you will definitely want to return for more. All types of biryani, from Malabar to Lucknowi, are delectable but Biryani Pilaf is just something great.</p><p><strong>9. Palak Puri</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Breakfast is traditionally eaten here with palak puri, which is a delicious and healthy dish. The most well-known street cuisine in Indore is palak puri. It is made by combining wheat dough with a paste of spinach leaves, some spices to boost the flavor, and then deep-frying it. The ideal accompaniments are raita, pickles, or hot potato curry. This dish is prepared in practically every home. Jabalpur is well known for it. This is unquestionably among the best ways to enjoy Popeye\'s preferred green vegetable. </p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>10. The Bhutte Ka Kees</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Bhutte Ka Kees is another wonderful and healthful cuisine. As the name implies, this staple street snack is made using bhuttas (corn). Grated corn kernels are cooked with a well-chosen assortment of seasonings and boiled with spices and skim milk, giving the meal a mildly sweet flavor. To improve the flavor of this treat, mustard seeds and green chilies are added. For fans of corn, this spicy, sweet nibble is a real pleasure. The greatest Bhutte Ka Kees can be found at Sarafa Bazaar in Indore.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Special mention: The Maharaja Royal Thaali</strong></p><p>A Thali is one of the best methods to learn about any regional cuisine. It is a filling supper that includes a variety of foods on one plate. Each regional Thali takes you on a culinary tour, allowing you to eat to your heart\'s delight while also learning about the local cuisine. Moving from region to region in a state like Madhya Pradesh allows you to sample a variety of cuisines to sate your hunger. However, the thali is a complete meal in and of itself and is one of the best ways to express the local culture of any place. </p><p>Maharaja Royal Thali in Rewa, in the northeastern region of Madhya Pradesh, is one of the delectable Thalis you must try when visiting. It is a true pleasure to sample a little bit of everything on this platter.</p><p>You won\'t know what to try first because of the wonderful range of dishes on this platter. You will be satiated with every delicious item on this platter and every mouthful you take.</p><p>A classic vegetarian Maharaja Royal Thali from Rewa is the ideal illustration of fine cuisine on an enormous plate. The thoughtful presentation of the appetizers, soup, pickles, entre, and desserts not only tempts but also pleases everyone.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Each wall of MP tells stories, lets hear!</strong></p><p>Madhya Pradesh because of its numerous forts, temples, and national parks is a great destination for a vacation. Whether you\'re interested in history or not, this location is more interesting than others in India because of the stunning architectural elements and several museums that educate visitors about historical events. So while you\'re trying to figure out where you want to go on your next summer vacation, have a look at this list of locations!</p><p>&nbsp;See what awaits you in this tranquil mood by looking at this list!</p><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Rare Interactions in Panna National Park</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Historical Visits in Sanchi</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Old City of Gwalior</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Exclusive Carvings and Sculptures at Khajuraho</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Capital City is Bhopal.</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Hampi of Central India is Mandu.</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Indore: The Center of Culture</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Jabalpur: Magnificent Beauty</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Tikamgarh: Peep Into the Past Pachmarhi: For Nature Lovers</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>1. Rare Interactions in Panna National Park</strong></p><p>In the Chhatarpur district, a stunning national park habitat nourishes species, unlike any other area in the state. This location is regarded as one of the top national parks to visit because it is the home of the mighty royal Bengal tigers. If you\'re fortunate, you could also be able to see sloth bears, chowsinghas, wolves, leopards, and hyenas in this area. Given its proximity to the tranquil hamlet of Khajuraho, this location has even more allure for its beautiful beauty.</p><p><strong>Location: Madhya Pradesh, Chhatarpur</strong></p><p><strong>2:30 p.m. to 5:30 p.m.</strong></p><p><strong>Entry Fee: For a group of six people, Jungle Safari charges INR 1000.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Historical Visits in Sanchi</strong></p><p>Sanchi, a city in the state\'s Raisen district, has a distinguished background that should not be overlooked on your next trip. Visit this center of Buddhism in the summer to see the well-known Sanchi Stupa, which was constructed by Ashoka. This city, which was formerly a hub for traders and merchants, is flanked by monasteries and toranas that provide tourists with a peaceful spiritual experience. Don\'t forget to visit the renowned archaeological museum nearby.</p><p><strong>Location: Madhya Pradesh\'s Raisen District</strong></p><p><strong>8:00 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.</strong></p><p><strong>Entry Fee: 10 INR</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Old City of Gwalior</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Gwalior has played a significant role in the development of the nation ever since the early Vedic era. This city has seen some incredible things, even during the times of the Mutiny, which have set the platform for more notable things to come, leading to the current stage. This city still has a lot to offer in terms of sightseeing despite having numerous locations of magnificent architecture. While you\'re here, be sure to visit Tansen Tomb, Man Singh Palace, and Gwalior Fort.</p><p><strong>Things to do in Gwalior: </strong></p><p><strong>Go To the Magnificent Gwalior Fort</strong></p><p><strong>Experience the Sasbahu Temple\'s Enchantment</strong></p><p><strong>Visit the Gujari Mahal Archaeological Museum and be awed by the grandeur of the Jai Vilas Palace Museum. You may also shop at the Patankar and Sarafa Bazaars.</strong></p><p><strong>Visit Tansen\'s Mausoleum to Pay Respects to the Musician</strong></p><p><strong>At Splash, beat the heat. The Suncity Marvel At The Rock-Cut Sculptures of Gopachal Parvat</strong></p><p><strong>Explore Teli Ka Mandir\'s architectural splendour and be mesmerised by the Sun Temple\'s beauty.</strong></p><p><strong>Visit Tighra Dam by boat</strong></p><p><strong>Visit Madhav National Park To View Wildlife</strong></p><p><strong>Check out the Gwalior Zoo</strong></p><p><strong>Beautiful Architecture of Bateshwar</strong></p><p><strong>Experience Coffee At An Indian Coffee Shop</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Khajuraho</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Khajuraho city serves as a source of national pride. The town\'s increased fame among tourists from around the world due to the presence of 22 temples adds to the whole experience of architecture and design work. Its worth noting how carefully these temples\' carvings and sculptures were created. Along with the lakes that are located in this small city, some of the must-see temples include Kandariya Mahadev Temple, Vishvanath Temple, and Duladeo Temple.</p><p><strong>Things to do: </strong></p><p>Explore the Khajuraho Temples</p><p>A Light and Sound Display Near the Western Group of Temples</p><p>Wander Around Khajuraho\'s Old Town</p><p>Explore Panna National Park To See Wildlife And Nature</p><p>Take In Khajuraho\'s Dance Festival</p><p>Visit the Ajaigarh Fort, number six.</p><p>Delight in Mouth-Watering Khajuraho Street Food</p><p>Visit Ayur Arogyam\'s Calming Ayurvedic Spa</p><p>Surrender to Nature at Raneh Falls Canyon 9. Discover History at the State Museum of Tribal and Folk Art</p><p>View the Pandav Waterfall\'s Mesmerizing Beauty</p><p>Examine Mastani Mahal\'s Ruins</p><p>Enjoy Beni Sagar Dam\'s View </p><p><strong>5. Bhopal</strong></p><p>Even while the influence of Muslim rulers is still evident in the picturesque city of Bhopal\'s well-known sites, this location is much more that meets the eye. The city\'s success has been accompanied by notable trends for others to follow thanks to good urban planning. The beauty of this area is further enhanced by locations like Moti Masjid, Taj-Ul-Masjid, Gufa Mandir, and Van Vihar. Don\'t miss out on the Toy train-like bus called \"Bhopal on Wheels\" in this city if you want to keep a variety of other things on your vacation as well. This is undoubtedly one of the top destinations in Madhya Pradesh to visit in the summer.</p><p><strong>Things to do: </strong></p><p>Sair Sapata: Enjoy Yourself and Have Fun</p><p>Take A Boat Ride Around Upper Lake</p><p>Enjoy Glorious Views on a Ropeway Ride</p><p>Take a Wildlife Safari Ride at Van Vihar National Park</p><p>Water Parks: Enjoy Yourself</p><p>Get Amused at the People\'s Mall</p><p>Shopping: Buy everything you can</p><p>Flying Fox Zip Lines at Kerwa Lake: Take a Ride</p><p>Enjoy the Exotic Food with Nawabi Cuisine</p><p>Visit museums to learn about vibrant culture and heritage.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>6. Indore: The Center for Culture</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>You name it, this city has itpalaces, museums, and temples. When you visit Indore, you\'ll understand why it\'s one of Madhya Pradesh\'s busiest citiesit has a certain appeal. From the perspective of a true traveler, this city offers a lot to all types of tourists. Prepare to experience more ecstasy at the Muhadi Falls or stroll through the Lalbagh Palace to learn more about the unique location\'s legends. In the summer, this is one among the top tourist destinations in Madhya Pradesh.</p><p><strong>Things to do: </strong></p><p>Admire the Incredible Architecture of Lal Bagh Palace</p><p>A Magnificent and Historical Palace: Rajwada</p><p>A great location for a hike and picnic is Patalpani Waterfalls.</p><p>Seek Blessing at the Annapurna Temple</p><p>Pipliyapala Regional Park: Experience the Best of Nature</p><p>Safari Activity Park is a beautiful learning facility. Mahatma Gandhi Town Hall is a historic landmark.</p><p>Tickle Your Taste Buds at Sarafa Bazar</p><p>Glass Temple Kanch Mandir</p><p>Trekkers Should Visit Janapav Kuti</p><p>Take a Quick Trip to Mandu</p><p>Great History Location: Indore Museum Buffs</p><p>Sacred Site for Jains: Gomatgiri</p><p>The Jyotirlinga of Shri Omkareshwar Visit Kothari Market - Crescent Water and Amusement Parks for the Shopaholics Have fun</p><p>Chappan Dukan: Savor the Delights</p><p>Take A Spiritual Journey To Ujjain\'s Ralamandal Wildlife Sanctuary, A Treat For Wildlife Lovers</p><p><strong>7. Mandu</strong></p><p>Mandu, known as the \"Hampi of Central India,\" has a long history that dates back to the 10th century A.D. This location has some impressive great architectural structures, and seeing some of the better ones will give you a glimpse into its illustrious past. While you\'re here, don\'t forget to stop by Rupmati\'s Pavilion, Jahaz Mahal, and Royal Enclave. If nothing else, you\'ll be in awe at the sunset vista from Rupmati\'s Pavilion.</p><p>Mandav, Madhya Pradesh is the location.</p><p>Visit Baz Bahadur\'s Palace, Hoshang Shah\'s Tomb, Neelkanth Temple, Rewa Kund, Dhar Fort</p><p><strong>8. Jabalpur: A Beautiful City</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>There is no better spot to spend your summer vacations than where sandstone and granite defend the majestic beauty. Jabalpur, one of the nicest places in the state to visit, offers a number of undiscovered jewels that you must see for yourself to believe. Dhuandhar Falls, Bhedaghat, Sangram Sagar, and Gurudwara Gwari Ghat Saheb are a few of these locations. Try the Gakkad-Bharta and Khoye ki Jalebi to indulge in the most genuine flavours of our country.</p><p><strong>Things to do: </strong></p><p>Find the camouflage by visiting the national reserves, Trekking Is A Must For A Supreme Taste Of Adventure, Sail out to learn to boat. Visit Museums: For Awesome Views, Take A Cable Car In Bhedaghat. Taste spicy food while enjoying Jabalpur\'s street food. Views From Madan Mahal Fort: Discover The Past. Discover Nature at the Ecotourism Site of Dumna Reserve Park. Pay respects and receive blessings at the Gwarighat Gurdwara. For The Adventure: Splash At Seaworld Water Park. Experience Spirituality at Chausath Yogini Temple: A Historic Site. Sangram Sagar Lake: A Quiet Place to Explore. Balancing Rock Dumna Nature Reserve Park, Marble Rocks. Rani Durgavati Museum in Bargi Dam</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>9. Pachmarhi: For Lovers of Nature</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Pachmarhi is among the top destination to visit in the summer. This lovely hill town is well known for its luxuriant forests, prehistoric paintings, tranquil waterfalls, breathtaking vistas, and more. Visit the lovely Silver Falls to enhance your trip with even more tranquilly and beauty. The vista from Sunset Point will mesmerize your senses unlike any other, even though the Pandav caverns are unquestionably worth visiting.</p><p><strong>Things to do: </strong></p><p>Horse riding, cave exploration, church visits, zip-lining, paragliding, hiking, waterfall trekking, hiking.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>10. Tikamgarh: A Look-Back</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Tikamgarh was formerly a part of Orchha and was established by the famed Bundela king Rudra Pratap Singh. Tikamgarh is a fantastic place to visit if you\'re searching for an exciting day trip from Orchha or Jhansi. The Tikamgarh Fort is one of the most popular attractions in this area, along with the Laxmi Narayan Temple, Dauji Ki Haveli, and Garhkundar Fort. Mahendra Sagar, which is located in this town, is also a good place to relax.</p><p><strong>Things to do: </strong></p><p>Visit Laxmi Narayan Temple, Dauji Ki Haveli, and Garhkundar Fort. Sunder Mahal, Jahangir Mahal and ramraja Mahal. </p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Well, we know Madhya Pradesh has a plethora of wildlife so below is a list for all the wildlife lovers to witness in the heart of India. </p><p>Some famous National Parks in Madhya Pradesh: </p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Satpura National Park and Biosphere</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bandhavgarh National Park</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kanha National Park</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pench National Park</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Madhav National Park</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Panna National Park and Tiger Reserve</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sanjay-Dubri National Park and Wildlife Sanctuary</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fossil National ParkVan Vihar National Park</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Madhya Pradesh is a stunning Indian state that is home to many great landmarks. You have a lot of options here when it comes to forts, too. The state is distinctive since it has been the scene of several historic events over the millennia. Madhya Pradesh, also referred to as the Heart of India, is a massive mashup of cultures thanks to its rich legacy and history. A list of all the forts you can explore on your trip to Madhya Pradesh:</p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Raisen Fort, Raisen</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Orchha Fort, Orchha</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mandu Fort, Mandu</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Maheshwar Fort, Khargone</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gwalior Fort, Gwalior</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dhar Fort, Dhar</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Datia Palace, Datia</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Asirgarh Fort, Burhanpur</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Reading all this is overwhelming, go and book your tickets to Indiss miraculous state now!</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Keywords </p><p>Madhya Pradesh history </p><p>Madhya Pradesh culture</p><p>Madhya Pradesh food</p><p>Places to travel in Madhya Pradesh</p><p>Why is mp famous</p><p>National parks in mp</p><p>Wildlife centuries in mp</p><p>Forts in mp</p><p>Things to do in mp</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '\"Discover the hidden gems of Madhya Pradesh: A comprehensive guide\", \"Madhya Pradesh\'s wildlife and adventure: A thrilling experience\", \"Exploring the history and culture of Madhya Pradesh: A journey back in time\", \"From ancient temples to modern architec', 'Omkareshwar temple Madhya Pradesh folk art, Satpura tiger reserve, Madhya Pradesh cuisine. Bhopal city tour, Madhya Pradesh offbeat destinations, Kanha National Park, Jabalpur Dhuandhar falls Pachmarhi hill station, Madhya Pradesh handicrafts, Ujjain Kumbh Mela, Chanderi handloom Madhya Pradesh tourism Khajuraho temples Wildlife safaris in Madhya Pradesh Orchha heritage town Gwalior fort Mandu historic city Sanchi stupa Bhimbetka rock shelters', '0', '219', 'N/A', 'N/A', '2023-02-27 18:28:58', '2023-02-27 18:28:58');
