(139, '35', 'West Bengal Wanderlust: Exploring the Cultural and Natural Treasures of Eastern India', 'general', 'west-bengal-wanderlust-exploring-the-cultural-and-natural-treasures-of-eastern-india', 'west-bengal-1678360136922115.jpeg', 'WEST BENGAL', 'West Bengal is a state in eastern India that is steeped in rich culture, history, and natural beauty. From the bustling city of Kolkata, with its colonial architecture and mouth-watering street food, to the serene tea estates of Darjeeling and the beautiful beaches of Digha, West Bengal offers a diverse range of experiences for travelers. Visitors can explore the state\'s wildlife sanctuaries and national parks, including the world-renowned Sundarbans, or immerse themselves in the vibrant local culture through festivals, music, and dance. With its unique blend of history, culture, and natural beauty, West Bengal is a fascinating destination that promises to enchant and inspire all who visit.', '<p><strong><em>A little on the history note</em></strong></p><p>A rich land that gave India jewels to cherish, West Bengal has a long and illustrious history of cultural and intellectual regimes. It has experienced it all over the years, from being a \"Rich Land with freedom fighters and intellectuals\" dating back to astonishing discoveries in Stone Age. India\'s fourth most populous state is located along the Bay of Bengal and makes up a large section of the country\'s eastern region.</p><p>A fascinating tourist destination, with Bhutan, Bangladesh, and Nepal as its boundaries. Kolkata, the capital city is a major metropolis with a long history as a presidential capital. Its signature beauty is the Rarh Region, the Ganga Deltas, and Darjeeling. It has given some of the most illustrious reformers. Sati was voiced by Raja Ram Mohan Roy. Untouchability and caste-based discrimination were brought under control by Ishwar Chandra and Swami Vivekananda.</p><p><strong><em>Culture that has evolves yet stays true to its roots. </em></strong></p><p>For a long time, Bengals artistic and literary achievements have eclipsed those of all other states in the country. The origins of music, dance, and folk literature may be traced back to the 10th and 11th centuries; Mangal Kavya, Dakshinaranjan Mitra, and Shree Krishna Kirtan are just a few of the well-known names for their masterworks in literature and poems. Bengali literature was modernized in the 19th and 20th centuries by writers such as Bankim Chandra. Madhusudan Dutt, a theatre pioneer, introduced blank verse. How can we forget our own Nobel Laureate, Rabindranath Tagore, who captured the hearts of all with his masterpieces in music and literature? He is the author of our country\'s National Anthem. Sarat Chandra Chattopadhyayshas shed light on contemporary social practises. Manik Bandyopadhyay is a well-known character in modern fiction and festivities.</p><p><strong><em>The marvelous festivities</em></strong></p><p>As unique and culturally rich as the state is so is its festivals, Durga Puja, which means \"love of the Bengali soil,\" is the most well-known event observed here. In the month of October, you can find women dressed in white and red sarees strolling the streets happily. The \"Sindoor Khela\" is a well-known custom from this period. Mahalaya is another well-known event that takes place before the start of the festival. Other festivals held are Chhat Puja and Poela Boisakh. If you wish to see a mix of cultural heritage and a variety of enthralling events with the most delicious festive food, then \"West Bengal\" is the place to go.</p><p><strong><em>The delicious cuisine </em></strong></p><p>It\'s not just about machh bhaat and sweets. It\'s much more than that, and it\'s a foodie\'s paradise for both vegetarians and non-vegetarians. Did you know that Bengali cuisine is the only cuisine on the Indian subcontinent with a genuine multi-course framework, much like current French cuisine? Bengalis enjoy their food and prefer it to be served in courses.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>When it comes to cuisine, there is a lot to discover. Bengali cuisine is culturally dynamic and simply lovely, ranging from Mughlai delicacies to street meals and an amazing variety of sweets and confectioneries, as well as the cuisine of the thriving Anglo-Indian population.</p><p>The following are the top ten foods that you must try while visiting West Bengal:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Shukto&nbsp;</em></strong></p><p>Shukto is a vegetarian treat made from bitter gourd, plantains, potatoes, and radishes and cooked in Bengali panch phorn, or the five spices that define Bengali cuisine. This is an unusual meal in Bengali cuisine, which is dominated by meat dishes. Get yourself invited to a Durga Pujo luncheon in a Bengali household if you want to sample traditional shukto. Suruchi, located at 89 Elliot Road in Kolkata, is another spot to try this dish. The restaurant is maintained by an all-women self-help organisation and serves delicious home-style cooking. Their Bengali thali is not to be missed.</p><p><strong><em>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kathi Rolls</em></strong></p><p>Who doesn\'t enjoy a good kathi roll? They were created in the City of Joy, after all! Bengalis are proud of this meal, which consists of thin rotis wrapped around skewer-roasted juicy meat kebabs. According to one school of thinking, the British invented the cuisine because they were too hygienic to touch the kebabs with their bare hands. Whatever the origin, one should not miss out on the best kathi rolls, which can be found at Nizam\'s and Badshah in Kolkata\'s New Market. Zaika, a shop on Park Street in Kolkata, also offers delicious kathi rolls.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Jhal Muri &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</em></strong></p><p>It\'s the Bengali counterpart of the bhel, if you will. Jhal Muri is another popular street meal in Bengal. Rice flakes (muri) are combined with roasted lentils and coconut chunks and mixed with spicy chutney and mustard oil. It\'s a convenient snack to have while driving around the city in the evening with a friend and having long-winded chats. The ultimate greatest site to try jhal muri is in Kolkata\'s Dacre Lane or Dacre Street, which has been praised by the WHO, who declared the food here to be the Best Street Food in the World!</p><p><strong><em>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Luchi alur dom</em></strong></p><p>For a relaxed Sunday breakfast, Luchi alur dom is the preferred Bengali combination. Luchi, which is comparable to puris, is served with alur dum, or aloo dom, which is a hotter and tangier variation of dum aloo. Head to Fairlie Road in Kolkata to have a dish of exquisite luchi-alur dom, which is a famous hangout for Bengali street food enthusiasts. A multitude of booths line the route, selling anything from rice and curries to kachuris (stuffed luchis). </p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Chingri Daab</em></strong></p><p>There\'s no doubting that Bengali cuisine\'s different types of fish curries are among the best in the world. If you\'re tired of fish and want to try something else, try the daab chingri, which are jumbo prawns cooked in mustard and served in delicate coconut. Oh! Calcutta is one of Kolkata\'s best-known eateries for its Daab Chingri. The nolen-gurer ice cream and the bhapa sondesh are two other dishes to try at this restaurant.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Keemar Doi Bora </em></strong></p><p>This wonderful marriage of minced meat and sweet and spicy curd will make non-vegetarian food and dahi bada lovers salivate. This is one of Bengal\'s less well-known street snacks. It has a long cultural connection with Nobel Laureate Rabindra Nath Tagore and his family, one of the most well-known Bengalis in the world. Purnima Thakur, who came into possession of the Tagore family cookbook, introduced the meal to the public as an original creation of the Thakurbari, as the Tagore family is called. You may try this delicious delicacy in Bara Bazaar or Burrabazaar in Kolkata.</p><p><strong><em>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ilish Maach or Shorshe Ilish</em></strong></p><p>Ilish Maach, Shorshe Ilish, or Ilish Bhapa is a tasty deep-fried Hilsa fish recipe. It\'s a traditional Bengali fish curry that\'s eaten with rice or Khichudi as a side dish. Both dried and curried versions are available. In Kolkata, the best spot to have an Ilish Bhapa is at Kasturi restaurant in Ballygunge.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bhetki Macher Paturi</em></strong></p><p>Ahoy, fish lovers! This one is guaranteed to put you in a state of blissful food coma. Bhetki Macher Paturi is a mouthwatering fish dish produced by slow cooking the fish in a mustard and coconut sauce and wrapping it in banana leaf. If you want to try the greatest bhetki macher paturi, you need hire a Rannar Thakur, a traditional Bengali professional cook. If you are unable to do so, visit 6 Ballygunge Place or Oh! Calcutta in Ballygunge and Elgin, accordingly.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kosha Mangsho&nbsp;</em></strong></p><p>Kosha Mangsho is for all mutton connoisseurs. This dish, which dates back to the British colonial era, consists of mutton cooked in a spicy tomato and yoghurt curry. Kosha is made with a variety of spices and fried in pure mustard oil. Golbari in Kolkata\'s Shyam Bazaar is THE place to go for a wonderful Kosha Mangsho meal. This 92-year-old eatery specialises in mutton cutlets, mutton kheema, and mutton chaap, among other mutton delicacies.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>10.Milk Sweets, Rasgullas, Chamcham, and Sondesh </em></strong></p><p>Bengali sweets are well-known throughout the world. They may make even the most averse to sweets drool and crave a piece of the decadent treats. Everything is a must-try, from rosogullas to sondesh and chamcham. If you don\'t indulge your sweet taste while in Bengal, you\'re committing a crime. Balaram Mullick and Radharam Mullick in Bhowanipore is the place to go in Kolkata for all things mishti. Baked rasgullas, which Calcuttans have learned to love, mango-flavored mishti doi, and a variety of flavoured sondesh are among the delectable sweets put up at this sweet heaven.</p><p><br></p><p><strong><em>Fetching travelers wanderlust!</em></strong></p><p>The trail to food starts with exploring the state and we are here for that. British were so enamored by West Bengal that they declared Kolkata to be their capital. Literature, culture, architecture, festivals, faiths, and gastronomy all collide in this diverse melting pot. When it comes to being one of India\'s greatest tourist attractions, it is unrivaled. Kolkata, known as the \"City of Joy,\" has been the subject of numerous historical films and literature. Darjeeling, the most popular hill station and tea plantation, is as well known for its tea as it is for its toy trains. Digha, a popular flat-surfaced beach, is also located here. Unquestionably one of the must-see destinations. If you\'re planning a vacation, you should look into these options.</p><p><strong><em>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mirik: A town out of fairytale</em></strong></p><p>Make a point of visiting Mirik, a little town around 50 kilometers from Darjeeling, if you ever visit Darjeeling. Mir-Yok, which means \"place burned by fire\" in Lepcha, is the name of this lovely and attractive town. Mirik boasts stunning landscapes that are filled with foliage all year because to the presence of numerous thick forests. The Sumendu lake, which features an arching bridge called the Rainbow bridge that connects the pine forest on one side of the lake to a garden on the other, is one of Mirik\'s main attractions. Mirik, at 1767 meters above sea level, has the ideal cool climate during the summer.</p><p>Trekking, boating, nature trails, and visiting the tea and orange plantations are all things to do in Mirik.</p><p>Ideal for: Everyone - couples, groups, solo travelers, and families</p><p>13 days is the ideal travel duration.</p><p>Summer temperatures range from 15 to 29 degrees, while winter temperatures range from 2 to 13 degrees.</p><p>March to Mid-June, and September to December are the best months to visit.</p><p><strong><em>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Darjeeling: Bengals Jewel</em></strong></p><p>Darjeeling, India\'s tea capital with some of the best tea gardens in the world and home to the famed \"Darjeeling Tea,\" is also one of the best tourist destinations in West Bengal throughout the summer due to its nice and temperate climate. It\'s affectionately referred to as the \"Queen of the Hills,\" and it\'s located close to Kanchenjunga, which towers over it like a big brother. Darjeeling is also home to the world-famous \"Darjeeling Himalayan Railway,\" better known as the toy train, which has been designated as a World Heritage Site by the United Nations. Darjeeling has something for everyone, whether you\'re a tea connoisseur, an adventurer, an art connoisseur, or a photographer or artist.</p><p>Trekking, hiking, water rafting, visiting tea estates, and mall hopping are among things to do in Darjeeling.</p><p>Ideal for: Everyone - couples, groups, solo travelers, and families</p><p>13 days is the ideal travel duration.</p><p>Summer temperatures range from 11 to 19 degrees, while winter temperatures range from 2 to -9 degrees.</p><p>March  Mid-June, October  December are the best months to visit.</p><p><strong><em>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kolkata: THE City of Joy</em></strong></p><p>The capital of West Bengal and the second-largest city in India is Kolkata. It is a celebration of human existence that never ends. West Bengal\'s capital is this vibrant 350-year-old metropolis on India\'s east coast. It thrives as India\'s cultural, intellectual, and social hub. Kolkata, also referred to as the \"City of Joy,\" is brimming with energy. The low cost of goods, the hand-pulled rickshaws, the winding streets, and the enormous variety of desserts are all expected to charm visitors. The Victoria Memorial, Howrah Bridge, Fort William, Eden Gardens, and Jorasanko Thakur Barithe ancestral house of Nobel Prize winner Rabindranath Tagoreare just a few of these magnificent city\'s highlights. Add this city to your bucket list because it is bursting with intriguing things to do!</p><p>Time needed: 2 to 3 days</p><p>What makes it unique: Old buildings, East Indian street food, and British-era artifacts.</p><p><strong><em>&nbsp;</em></strong></p><p><strong><em>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kurseong</em></strong><span style=\"color: black;\"> </span><strong><em>home of Orchids</em></strong></p><p>If you enjoy flowers and orchids, Kurseong is a must-see destination for you, as it is home to some of India\'s most magnificent orchid gardens. This tranquil highland station is called locally \"Kharsang,\" which translates as \"Land of White Orchids\" in Lepcha. Kurseong, at 1458 meters above sea level, has a beautiful climate all year and is a popular destination for travelers visiting Darjeeling because it is only 30 kilometers away. Kurseong is also a station for the famed Darjeeling toy train, so you can take the toy train from Darjeeling to explore this beautiful spot with plenty of photo opportunities. </p><p>Tourists adore Kurseong because it is one of the best spots to visit in West Bengal during the summer, which is why it is included in almost every itinerary.</p><p>Trekking, hiking, water rafting, and adventure sports are among the activities available in Kurseong.</p><p>Ideal for: Everyone - couples, groups, solo travelers, and families</p><p>13 days is the ideal travel duration.</p><p>Summer temperatures range from 8 to 20 degrees, while winter temperatures range from 3 to 10 degrees.</p><p>March to Mid-June, and September to December are the best months to visit.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;lava</em></strong></p><p>Visiting Lava is like going back in time, as it is a town that has remained unaffected by modernity and cherishes its values and culture. Lava, an undiscovered gem till recently, is one of the best spots to visit in West Bengal during the summer for people seeking a fascinating, calm holiday with lush alpine woods and magnificent vistas of the majestic Mount Kanchenjunga. The Lava Monastery of the Buddhists, which is designed in the Tibetan style of architecture, is also located in Lava. One of the best locations to visit in Lava is the unique Nature Interpretation Centre, which is located near the monastery.</p><p>In Lava, there are a variety of things to do. Trekking, hiking, bird watching, and adventure sports are all popular activities.</p><p>Ideal for: Everyone - couples, groups, solo travelers, and families</p><p>12 days is the ideal travel duration.</p><p>Summer temperatures range from 10 to 30 degrees, while winter temperatures range from 7 to 16 degrees.</p><p>October to April is the best time to visit.</p><p><strong><em>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Digha: beach place</em></strong></p><p>If you enjoy the beach, then Digha is the ideal location for your next vacation. It has one of India\'s and the world\'s longest coasts, measuring 7 kilometres in length. The flat beachfront of the Digha beach makes it ideal for relaxing and watching the sunset with loved ones. Bengal\'s first Governor-General Warren Hastings dubbed Digha \"Brighton of the East\" in recognition of its splendour. The route to Digha beach is also particularly scenic, as it is flanked on both sides by casuarina trees. Digha also includes a few historical temples and museums where you may learn more about the city\'s history and culture.</p><p>Water sports, swimming, and beach sports are among the activities available in Digha.</p><p>Ideal for: Everyone - couples, groups, solo travellers, and families</p><p>12 days is the ideal travel duration.</p><p>The best time to visit is between October and March.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Medieval Capital: Gaur-Pandua</em></strong></p><p>The stunning ruins of the Muslim Sultans\' era\'s architecture may be found in Gaur-Pandua, one of West Bengal\'s mediaeval cities. Mosques and tombs including the Baro Sona Masjid, the Tomb of Fateh Khan, the Adina Masjid, and the Eklakhi Mausoleum make up the majority of the remains. The district of Malda, commonly known as the Mango City, is where these twin settlements are situated. Don\'t forget to stop here and purchase some delectable mangoes and Murshidabad silk.</p><p>Location: West Bengal\'s Malda District</p><p>Two days are needed.</p><p>What makes it unique: Enchanting mediaeval ruins.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sandakphu: Panormic Town</em></strong></p><p>Sandakphu, the highest peak in the vicinity and one of the greatest places to visit in West Bengal during the summer, is the spot to go if you want a panoramic view of snow-capped mountains. This location, located on the Singalila Ridge on the West Bengal-Nepal border, offers the greatest views of the Kangchenjunga range, which attracts many hikers and trekkers. The temperature reduces during the summer, making it a great spot to visit for everyone. You cannot afford to miss West Bengal if you are planning a holiday with your buddies.</p><p>&nbsp;Trekking, photography, and sightseeing are among the activities available in Sandakphu.</p><p>Trekkers and nature enthusiasts would enjoy this.</p><p>Trip duration: 2-3 days is ideal.</p><p>April to May, October to early December are the best months to visit.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mangrove Land: The Sundarbans</em></strong></p><p>The largest mangrove eco-arrangement in the world is located at this UNESCO World Heritage Site. It is the world\'s largest estuarine forest, bewildered by several streams and tributaries, joined by a system of tidal conduits, and a tangle of tiny mangrove islands. It is also home to one of India\'s most notorious untamed living species, the Royal Bengal Tiger. The Sundarbans are one of the most alluring and lovely places on earth because of their connectivity. 250 tigers and a variety of birds, reptiles, and invertebrates, including crocodiles, live in this remarkable territory at the moment. About 110 kilometers separate Kolkata from this natural paradise.</p><p>5 to 6 hours are needed.</p><p>What makes it unique: Trekking through India\'s beautiful nature reserve and viewing white tigers.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>10.Pedong</em></strong></p><p>Pedong will enchant you with its bucolic environment if you are looking for a tranquil area in West Bengal. The most breathtaking views of the eastern Himalayan peaks may be found in this settlement, which is located in the Kalimpong district. The Pedong Monastery, which is full of monks, prayer bells, and a pleasant air, is one of the best sites to visit here. People who want to get away from the city and the tourist crowds frequently come to Pedong and stay for a few days. Explore the Pedong Monastery and Rishi Khola, go for natural hikes, and socialise with the locals in Pedong.</p><p>Ideal for: Those looking for peace</p><p>2 days is the ideal travel duration.</p><p>AprilMay, OctoberMarch are the best months to visit.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>11.Shantiniketan: Peace and Quiet at Their Finest</em></strong></p><p>A town in West Bengal\'s Birbhum district, Shantiniketan is around 212 kilometres from Kolkata. Rabindranath Tagore, a Nobel Prize winner, lived there and is credited with putting it on the map. The location, which is now a university, now gets a lot of tourists every year. Be sure to check out the area\'s various attractions, including Tagore\'s Ashrama, Poush Mela, Amar Kutir, and Rabindra Bhaban Museum, where you can see a variety of the artist\'s sculptures and paintings.</p><p>Birbhum, West Bengal, is the location.</p><p>Two to three days are needed.</p><p>Special features: Home to numerous popular attractions.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>12.Cooch Behar: Man-made Marvels</em></strong></p><p>&nbsp;Cooch BeharCooch Behar is renowned for its upscale ambiance, pristine beauty, and grandeur. The Pala-Senas ruled Cooch Behar in the eleventh and twelfth centuries. The royal home of Koch ruler Maharaja Nripendra Narayan is Cooch Behar\'s main draw. The Maharaja constructed this magnificent palace in 1887 with the intention of making it mimic the classic European architecture of the Italian Renaissance. Make a point of visiting Cooch Behar if you enjoy history.</p><p>West Bengal\'s Cooch Behar District is the location.</p><p>Two to three days are needed.</p><p>What makes it unique: Maharaja Nripendra Narayan of Koch\'s regal home.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>13.Gateway To The North East: Siliguri</em></strong></p><p>&nbsp;Siliguri, a charming city located in Jalpaiguri, is known as the entry point to the country\'s North East. Siliguri, one of the most stunning tourist destinations in West Bengal, has an international airport and is frequently used as a stopover before visitors travel to other cities to explore. However, Siliguri has a lot more to offer. This city is one of the most refreshing ones of all because it is completely covered with natural wonders, such as lush green trees and beautiful national parks. The Jaldapara National Park, which encompasses a lovely rivering forest and wide meadows, is a must-see location in Siliguri.</p><p>What makes it unique: The lush vegetation and breathtaking vistas.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>14.Durgapur</em></strong></p><p>Sometimes known as the \"Steel Capital of East India,\" is a city in West Bengal that is located on the banks of the Damodar River. Durgapur is one of the excellent tourist destinations in West Bengal that should not be missed since it offers the best fusion of small-town feelings with big city excitement. Old-fashioned marketplaces, glittering temples, and sizable parks can all be found in this town for children to enjoy their free time. This town, located in the heart of West Bengal, has a lot more to offer. When visiting Durgapur, do not overlook the local cuisine.</p><p>What\'s unique: reflects the spirit of West Bengal with its tranquil temples and ancient bazaar.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><em>15.Dooars  Gateway To Bhutan </em></strong></p><p>If you want to spend your vacation just chilling and unwinding, Dooars is one of the best spots to go in West Bengal. It is renowned for its powerful range of mountains, dense woods, rich flora and wildlife, and tea gardens. It is one of the top tourist sites in West Bengal. These floodplains extend from the Teesta River to the Sankoshi River. Since these floodplains are the \"doorways\" of Bhutan, the name \"Dooars\" derives from the word \"doors.\"</p><p>Two to three days are needed.</p><p>What makes it unique: Mesmerizing mountain vistas.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class=\"ql-align-center\"><strong>A QUICK HELP KIT FOR A TRIP TO WEST BENGAL</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Hill stations</strong></p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Darjeeling</p><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kalimpong</p><p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mirik </p><p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Namchi</p><p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pelling</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Wildlife sanctuaries</strong></p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Senchal Wildlife Sanctuary</p><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Buxa Tiger Reserve</p><p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sajnekhali Wildlife Sanctuary</p><p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ramnabagan Wildlife Sanctuary</p><p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Jore Pokhri Wildlife Sanctuary</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Waterfalls</strong></p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Changey Waterfalls</p><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ghagra Waterfalls</p><p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Chunnu Waterfalls</p><p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Paglajhora Waterfalls</p><p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Turga Waterfall</p><p>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Rainbow Waterfalls</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Must-Visit Places in West Bengal</strong></p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kolkata: Howrah Bridge, Jorasanko Thakurbari, Park Street, Indian Museum, Victoria Memorial, Dakshineswar Kali Temple, St. Pauls Cathedral, Kalighat Kali Temple, Science City, Mother House</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>Darjeeling: <span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Darjeeling Himalayan Railway, Singalila National Park, Padmaja Naidu Himalayan Zoological Park,Tiger Hill, Observatory Hill, Happy Valley Tea Estate, Japanese Peace Pagoda, Neora Valley National Park, Mirik, Rock Garden</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>Siliguri: <span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Kali Mandir, Chilapata Forests, Salugara Monastery, Coronation Bridge, Mahananda Weir Wildlife Sanctuary</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><br></p><p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Murshidabad : Kali Mandir, Chilapata Forests, Salugara Monastery, Coronation Bridge, Mahananda Weir Wildlife Sanctuary</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Coach Behar: Cooch Behar Palace, Chilapata Forest Range, Rasik Bil, Madan Mohan Bari, Dangar Ayee Temple</p><p>We have only included a small number of well-known tourist destinations. Nevertheless, there are still plenty of other stunning locations to explore, including the border\'s tranquil picturesque villages, the bustling district cities with a distinctly vintage vibe, the state\'s southernmost turquoise water bodies, and beautiful historic remains. A keen traveler who has yet to reveal many of the undiscovered layers will find West Bengal to be a gem!</p><p>So on your next travel vacation, do not forget to add these marvelous places on the list.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'The Ultimate Guide to Traveling in West Bengal: From Kolkata to the Himalayas, Uncovering the Charm of West Bengal: A Journey Through History, Culture, and Adventure, West Bengal Wonder: A Tour of India\'s Most Enchanting State Experience the Best of West ', 'West Bengal tourism Places to visit in West Bengal Best tourist places in West Bengal West Bengal travel guide West Bengal tour packages West Bengal tourist attractions West Bengal hill stations Beaches in West Bengal West Bengal historical places West Bengal adventure activities West Bengal wildlife sanctuaries West Bengal cultural festivals West Bengal food and cuisine West Bengal offbeat destinations West Bengal weekend getaways', '0', '219', 'N/A', 'N/A', '2023-03-09 11:08:57', '2023-03-09 11:08:57');
